</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1127,749,1542]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">Thorax ventrally with coarse brown punctures, which are more sparse on metapleura; peritreme ochraceous. Metapleura swollen, its postero-lateral corners visible in dorsal view.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1127,749,1542]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">
Legs ochraceous, apices of tibiae and tarsomeres 2 slightly blackened; hind femur and tibia with inner margin granulated, femur slightly swollen and curved inwards, tibia straight. Abdomen with only connexival spines visible from above; ventrally ochraceous, sterna 3-6 each with small black spot on each side near middle; median carina on sterna 3-6 well developed; postero-lateral angles of sterna 3-5 with small spines, sternum 6 with long posterolaterally directed spine on each side; sternum 7 parallel-sided, postero-lateral angles strongly produced posteriad; posterior margin of sternum 8 slightly incised medially (
<figureCitation box="[966,1032,1005,1030]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[113,152,1493,1512]" captionTargetBox="[114,1065,227,1462]" captionTargetId="figure-16@5.[114,1065,220,1467]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 1-5. Mahea sexualis Distant, 1909. 1 – head, dorsal view; 2 – pronotum, dorsal view; 3 – pronotum, posterior view; 4 – abdomen of male (lectotype), ventral view; 5 – abdomen of female (paralectotype), ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4476402" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4476402/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1127,749,1542]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">
Pygophore (
<figureCitation box="[309,403,1037,1061]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="6.[151,190,654,673]" captionTargetBox="[151,1126,220,628]" captionTargetId="figure-323@6.[151,1126,220,628]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs. 6-7. Mahea sexualis Distant, 1909. Pygophore (lectotype). 6 – posterior view; 7 – ventral view. Scale bars 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4476404" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4476404/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">Figs. 6-7</figureCitation>
) brownish, dorso-ventrally flattened, postero-lateral angles each with tuft of long setae; parameres apically pointed, ventrally with setigerous punctures.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1127,749,1542]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">
Female (
<typeStatus box="[276,422,1101,1125]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">paralectotype</typeStatus>
) (
<figureCitation box="[445,523,1101,1126]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[113,152,1493,1512]" captionTargetBox="[114,1065,227,1462]" captionTargetId="figure-16@5.[114,1065,220,1467]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 1-5. Mahea sexualis Distant, 1909. 1 – head, dorsal view; 2 – pronotum, dorsal view; 3 – pronotum, posterior view; 4 – abdomen of male (lectotype), ventral view; 5 – abdomen of female (paralectotype), ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4476402" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4476402/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">Fig. 41</figureCitation>
). Length 
<quantity box="[632,718,1102,1126]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.2" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" unit="mm" value="8.2">8.2 mm</quantity>
, width of pronotum between humeral angles approximately 4.1 mm (right spine missing); punctures on body reddish; metapleura only slightly swollen, less prominent in dorsal view; abdomen (
<figureCitation box="[823,886,1165,1189]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[113,152,1493,1512]" captionTargetBox="[114,1065,227,1462]" captionTargetId="figure-16@5.[114,1065,220,1467]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 1-5. Mahea sexualis Distant, 1909. 1 – head, dorsal view; 2 – pronotum, dorsal view; 3 – pronotum, posterior view; 4 – abdomen of male (lectotype), ventral view; 5 – abdomen of female (paralectotype), ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4476402" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4476402/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
) less narrowing posteriad, more flattened, unicolorous, without black round spots, median carina developed only on sterna 3-4; connexival spines as in 
<figureCitation box="[556,620,1229,1253]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[113,152,1493,1512]" captionTargetBox="[114,1065,227,1462]" captionTargetId="figure-16@5.[114,1065,220,1467]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 1-5. Mahea sexualis Distant, 1909. 1 – head, dorsal view; 2 – pronotum, dorsal view; 3 – pronotum, posterior view; 4 – abdomen of male (lectotype), ventral view; 5 – abdomen of female (paralectotype), ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4476402" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4476402/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1127,749,1542]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,277,1261,1285]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">Variability.</emphasis>
Male 
<typeStatus box="[346,489,1261,1285]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">paralectotype</typeStatus>
differs from the 
<typeStatus box="[670,767,1261,1285]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">lectotype</typeStatus>
in having the clypeus completely enclosed by mandibular plates; body length 
<quantity box="[606,687,1294,1318]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.4" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" unit="mm" value="7.4">7.4 mm</quantity>
, length of antennomere 2 equal to 
<quantity box="[1039,1124,1294,1318]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" unit="mm" value="2.4">2.4 mm</quantity>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,399,1325,1349]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1909" box="[405,570,1325,1349]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" genus="Mahea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sexualis">
<emphasis box="[405,570,1325,1349]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">Mahea sexualis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cachan" authorityYear="1952" box="[710,824,1325,1349]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" genus="Muschalea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="andriai">
<emphasis box="[710,824,1325,1349]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">M. andriai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[837,951,1325,1349]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" genus="Mahea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="distanti" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[837,951,1325,1349]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">M. distanti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[958,1043,1326,1349]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" genus="Mahea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parvula">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">M. parvula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having each humeral angle abruptly produced into a long spine, not conical. From 
<taxonomicName box="[151,268,1389,1413]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" genus="Mahea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="durrelli" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[151,268,1389,1413]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">M. durrelli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[276,360,1390,1413]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
it differs by having the lateral pronotal margins regularly sinuated, the humeral spines not raised (
<figureCitation box="[442,541,1421,1446]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[113,152,1493,1512]" captionTargetBox="[114,1065,227,1462]" captionTargetId="figure-16@5.[114,1065,220,1467]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 1-5. Mahea sexualis Distant, 1909. 1 – head, dorsal view; 2 – pronotum, dorsal view; 3 – pronotum, posterior view; 4 – abdomen of male (lectotype), ventral view; 5 – abdomen of female (paralectotype), ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4476402" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4476402/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">Figs. 2-3</figureCitation>
), the metapleura distinctly swollen, differently shaped connexival spines (
<figureCitation box="[350,445,1453,1477]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[113,152,1493,1512]" captionTargetBox="[114,1065,227,1462]" captionTargetId="figure-16@5.[114,1065,220,1467]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 1-5. Mahea sexualis Distant, 1909. 1 – head, dorsal view; 2 – pronotum, dorsal view; 3 – pronotum, posterior view; 4 – abdomen of male (lectotype), ventral view; 5 – abdomen of female (paralectotype), ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4476402" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4476402/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">Figs. 4-5</figureCitation>
), and apex of each paramere pointed (
<figureCitation box="[834,928,1453,1477]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="6.[151,190,654,673]" captionTargetBox="[151,1126,220,628]" captionTargetId="figure-323@6.[151,1126,220,628]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs. 6-7. Mahea sexualis Distant, 1909. Pygophore (lectotype). 6 – posterior view; 7 – ventral view. Scale bars 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4476404" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4476404/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">Figs. 6-7</figureCitation>
) (see also the key).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1127,749,1542]" box="[151,376,1485,1509]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,258,1485,1509]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">Bionomy.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[151,969,1517,1542]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1127,749,1542]" box="[151,969,1517,1542]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,295,1517,1541]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">Distribution.</emphasis>
Island of Mahé (
<collectingCountry box="[477,596,1517,1541]" name="Seychelles" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">Seychelles</collectingCountry>
). Known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[849,895,1518,1542]" pageId="6" pageNumber="27">type</typeStatus>
series.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="28" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[113,1090,223,887]" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,242,223,247]" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">Comments.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="DISTANT W. L." box="[249,409,223,247]" pageId="7" pageNumber="28" pagination="29 - 47" refId="ref13166" refString="DISTANT W. L. 1909: The Percy Sladen trust expedition to the Indian Ocean in 1905, under the leadership of Mr. J. Stanley Gardiner. Volume II. No. IV. &quot; Sealark &quot; Rhynchota. Transactions of the Linnean Society of London, Zoology 13 (1): 29 - 47 + 1 pl." type="journal article" year="1909">DISTANT (1909)</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1909" box="[525,646,223,247]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" genus="Mahea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sexualis">
<emphasis box="[525,646,223,247]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">M. sexualis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on both sexes, but he did not mention the number or the location of 
<typeStatus box="[490,586,256,280]" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">syntypes</typeStatus>
. The type locality was given unambigously as ‘Locality. Mahé’, but on the next line 
<bibRefCitation author="DISTANT W. L." box="[513,672,287,311]" pageId="7" pageNumber="28" pagination="29 - 47" refId="ref13166" refString="DISTANT W. L. 1909: The Percy Sladen trust expedition to the Indian Ocean in 1905, under the leadership of Mr. J. Stanley Gardiner. Volume II. No. IV. &quot; Sealark &quot; Rhynchota. Transactions of the Linnean Society of London, Zoology 13 (1): 29 - 47 + 1 pl." type="journal article" year="1909">DISTANT (1909)</bibRefCitation>
wrote: ‘Dr. Schouteden has kindly sent me a male specimen of this species from 
<collectingCountry box="[550,683,319,343]" name="Madagascar" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
.’ The description was accompanied by a figure of a female from 
<collectingCountry box="[386,446,351,375]" name="India" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">Mahé</collectingCountry>
and a male from 
<collectingCountry box="[633,763,351,375]" name="Madagascar" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[113,1090,223,887]" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">
<bibRefCitation author="KUMAR R." box="[144,297,383,407]" pageId="7" pageNumber="28" pagination="1 - 60" refId="ref13645" refString="KUMAR R. 1974: A revision of world Acanthosomatidae (Heteroptera: Pentatomoidea): Keys to and descriptions of subfamilies, tribes and genera, with designation of types. Australian Journal of Zoology, Supplementary Series 34: 1 - 60." type="book chapter" year="1974">KUMAR (1974)</bibRefCitation>
examined three specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1909" box="[629,751,383,407]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" genus="Mahea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sexualis">
<emphasis box="[629,751,383,407]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">M. sexualis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
deposited in the BMNH – one male and one female from 
<collectingCountry box="[401,464,415,439]" name="India" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">Mahé</collectingCountry>
, and one male from 
<collectingCountry box="[684,814,415,439]" name="Madagascar" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
. He wrote: ‘… the 
<collectingCountry name="Madagascar" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
male is a distinct species, quite different from 
<collectingCountry box="[679,739,447,471]" name="India" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">Mahé</collectingCountry>
specimens. … Distant’s description covers both species and his type label is affixed to the 
<collectingCountry box="[754,882,479,503]" name="Madagascar" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
specimen. In these circumstances, I have taken the 
<collectingCountry box="[451,579,511,535]" name="Madagascar" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
specimen to be the type and have placed a label on it indicating this is the 
<typeStatus box="[390,486,543,567]" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">holotype</typeStatus>
. The species represented by the specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[1004,1064,543,567]" name="India" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">Mahé</collectingCountry>
is being described elswhere.’ The 
<collectingCountry box="[455,583,575,599]" name="Madagascar" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
specimen, however, did not originate from the type locality, and thus it cannot be a 
<typeStatus box="[528,611,608,632]" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">syntype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1909" box="[653,776,607,631]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" genus="Mahea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sexualis">
<emphasis box="[653,776,607,631]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">M. sexualis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
either by 
<bibRefCitation author="DISTANT W. L." box="[893,1056,607,631]" pageId="7" pageNumber="28" pagination="29 - 47" refId="ref13166" refString="DISTANT W. L. 1909: The Percy Sladen trust expedition to the Indian Ocean in 1905, under the leadership of Mr. J. Stanley Gardiner. Volume II. No. IV. &quot; Sealark &quot; Rhynchota. Transactions of the Linnean Society of London, Zoology 13 (1): 29 - 47 + 1 pl." type="journal article" year="1909">DISTANT (1909)</bibRefCitation>
or 
<bibRefCitation author="KUMAR R." box="[113,265,639,663]" pageId="7" pageNumber="28" pagination="1 - 60" refId="ref13645" refString="KUMAR R. 1974: A revision of world Acanthosomatidae (Heteroptera: Pentatomoidea): Keys to and descriptions of subfamilies, tribes and genera, with designation of types. Australian Journal of Zoology, Supplementary Series 34: 1 - 60." type="book chapter" year="1974">KUMAR (1974)</bibRefCitation>
. The 
<typeStatus box="[317,413,639,663]" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">lectotype</typeStatus>
designation by 
<bibRefCitation author="KUMAR R." box="[573,721,639,663]" pageId="7" pageNumber="28" pagination="1 - 60" refId="ref13645" refString="KUMAR R. 1974: A revision of world Acanthosomatidae (Heteroptera: Pentatomoidea): Keys to and descriptions of subfamilies, tribes and genera, with designation of types. Australian Journal of Zoology, Supplementary Series 34: 1 - 60." type="book chapter" year="1974">KUMAR (1974)</bibRefCitation>
is therefore unjustified and in valid.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[113,1090,223,887]" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">
I had the opportunity to study three specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1909" box="[674,795,671,695]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" genus="Mahea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sexualis">
<emphasis box="[674,795,671,695]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">M. sexualis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
– one male and one female from BMNH, and one male from CUMZ – with the same locality labels and determination labels written most probably by the same hand (see Type material). Therefore, I regard all these specimens to be 
<typeStatus box="[358,451,768,792]" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">syntypes</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1909" box="[490,612,767,791]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" genus="Mahea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sexualis">
<emphasis box="[490,612,767,791]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">M. sexualis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The male from CUMZ was choosen as the 
<typeStatus box="[113,210,799,823]" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">lectotype</typeStatus>
because it is better preserved and has the pygophore, which is lost in the male from BMNH. The 
<collectingCountry box="[256,384,831,855]" name="Madagascar" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
specimen designated as a 
<typeStatus box="[669,766,831,855]" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">lectotype</typeStatus>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="KUMAR R. &amp; GHAURI M. S. K." box="[808,960,831,855]" pageId="7" pageNumber="28" pagination="1 - 31" refId="ref13690" refString="KUMAR R. &amp; GHAURI M. S. K. 1970: Morphology and relationships of the Pentatomoidea (Heteroptera 2 - World genera of Tessaratomini (Tessaratomidae). Deutsche Entomologische Zeitschrift 17: 1 - 31." type="journal article" year="1970">Kumar (1970)</bibRefCitation>
is currently described as 
<taxonomicName box="[251,366,863,887]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" genus="Mahea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="distanti" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[251,366,863,887]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="28">M. distanti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[373,456,864,887]" pageId="7" pageNumber="28" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
